00:00:22.063 --> 00:00:24.230
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So
today, we really kind of talk

00:00:24.230 --> 00:00:27.800
more about the system, the
kind of third direct innovation

00:00:27.800 --> 00:00:31.790
factor, and then about
these indirect factors that

00:00:31.790 --> 00:00:36.093
are important and significant,
but not as powerful, I'd argue,

00:00:36.093 --> 00:00:37.010
as the direct factors.

00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:45.150
But first, let me just
recap last week just really

00:00:45.150 --> 00:00:47.858
in a few seconds,
and then give us

00:00:47.858 --> 00:00:49.400
a glimpse of what
we're getting into.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:57.830
So last week, Robert Solow,
the great growth economist,

00:00:57.830 --> 00:01:02.810
developed-- really
created growth economics--

00:01:02.810 --> 00:01:06.890
developed the theory that
the dominant causative

00:01:06.890 --> 00:01:08.870
factor in economic
growth was, quote,

00:01:08.870 --> 00:01:10.980
technological and
related innovation,

00:01:10.980 --> 00:01:13.742
a phrase that you'll
hear all the time here.

00:01:13.742 --> 00:01:17.660
And then we followed up
that discussion with talk

00:01:17.660 --> 00:01:20.510
about Paul Romer and his
work on human capital

00:01:20.510 --> 00:01:26.450
engaged in research as a kind
of second key direct innovation

00:01:26.450 --> 00:01:27.740
factor.

00:01:27.740 --> 00:01:33.170
That's the talent base that has
to be behind the R&D system.

00:01:33.170 --> 00:01:39.440
We read Dale Jorgenson who
told us that, yes, in fact,

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:43.400
this innovation based
economic growth model

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:44.690
is in fact correct.

00:01:44.690 --> 00:01:46.400
That's what happened
in the IT wave

00:01:46.400 --> 00:01:49.625
and he showed us, in
effect, how that occurred.

00:01:52.490 --> 00:01:57.550
The model was you do an
invention or a core group

00:01:57.550 --> 00:02:00.910
of inventions, they
begin to scale up,

00:02:00.910 --> 00:02:04.960
applications pile on them,
they enter into the economy

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:07.720
and really begin to
scale up in the economy.

00:02:07.720 --> 00:02:11.110
And eventually, over time,
become a true innovation wave.

00:02:11.110 --> 00:02:13.720
And we'll talk more today, as
you know, about innovation wave

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:15.130
theory.

00:02:15.130 --> 00:02:20.650
We also read a piece by
some Merrill Lynch analysts,

00:02:20.650 --> 00:02:24.670
and the fundamental
point in that piece

00:02:24.670 --> 00:02:27.370
was that industry is very
interested in innovation,

00:02:27.370 --> 00:02:31.960
but they're only prepared to
fund the very short late stage

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:33.160
of it.

00:02:33.160 --> 00:02:37.360
So somehow, even though
the evolution to innovation

00:02:37.360 --> 00:02:42.310
is a very long-term process,
the financial sector

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:44.740
is only going to
dive in as close

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:46.970
as they can to certainty--
in other words,

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:48.910
at a very late stage.

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:53.480
So those were kind of
our four core readings.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:56.590
And one other idea in
that Merrill Lynch piece

00:02:56.590 --> 00:02:59.890
was this notion that
innovation needs

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:02.590
to move through a series of
stages to kind of get there.

00:03:02.590 --> 00:03:05.740
There needs to be
an early vision--

00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:09.130
kind of a visionary who will
set out what could happen.

00:03:09.130 --> 00:03:12.220
And then enabling
technologies evolve

00:03:12.220 --> 00:03:15.880
that become technical
enablers for the evolution

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:18.040
to an innovation wave.

00:03:18.040 --> 00:03:20.745
And then there's going to be
substantial talent on task.

00:03:20.745 --> 00:03:22.870
In other words, people have
got to be-- researchers

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:26.770
have got to be working on this
in significant depth in order

00:03:26.770 --> 00:03:28.180
for this thing to evolve.

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:31.990
So it's going to take a
community scale kind of effort.

00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.390
So the first class
left us with two

00:03:34.390 --> 00:03:37.660
direct or explicit
innovation factors.

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:39.930
And we could in a--

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:42.790
oversimplify them and
put them in shorthand,

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:44.410
but we could say
you've got to do R&D

00:03:44.410 --> 00:03:48.190
and you've got to have a talent
base staffing that R&D system.

00:03:48.190 --> 00:03:53.200
And we worked on a definition
of innovation as a system

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:55.240
for introducing
technical advance,

00:03:55.240 --> 00:03:59.740
and we talked briefly about
innovation waves, which

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:02.050
we'll spend more time on today.

00:04:02.050 --> 00:04:08.590
So that's a quick recap
of last week's discussion.

00:04:08.590 --> 00:04:12.670
And Chris, you and
I can follow up

00:04:12.670 --> 00:04:15.820
so you catch up on some of
the issues that came up there.

00:04:15.820 --> 00:04:19.042
And I've posted the slides
to the STELLAR site which

00:04:19.042 --> 00:04:21.459
will help as well, but I'd be
happy to talk to you further

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:22.146
about it.

00:04:25.270 --> 00:04:27.610
So let me just do
a quick snapshot

00:04:27.610 --> 00:04:29.470
to open up today's discussion.

00:04:29.470 --> 00:04:31.300
So that's Thomas Edison.

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:44.010
That's his idea factory
and that's the group

00:04:44.010 --> 00:04:47.550
that does the light bulb.

00:04:47.550 --> 00:04:51.550
It's the light bulb
and you can see

00:04:51.550 --> 00:04:54.730
the idea factory-- this building
in that scheme at the top.

00:04:54.730 --> 00:04:56.500
And then you can
see the farmhouse

00:04:56.500 --> 00:04:58.177
back behind which
is where Edison

00:04:58.177 --> 00:05:00.760
lived with his wife except that
he never spent any time there.

00:05:00.760 --> 00:05:04.810
He was in the idea
factory pretty much 24/7.

00:05:04.810 --> 00:05:06.820
I just want to give
you a feel for what

00:05:06.820 --> 00:05:09.250
innovation is like when
it starts to take off.

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:10.510
And this is a good--

00:05:10.510 --> 00:05:13.000
Edison is a classic example.

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.380
So he-- very limited education.

00:05:17.380 --> 00:05:19.750
He was homeschooled
by his mother.

00:05:19.750 --> 00:05:22.870
He's probably pretty dyslexic.

00:05:22.870 --> 00:05:27.250
We don't quite know that,
but it's probably the case.

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:32.050
As a kid, he understands
the early evolution

00:05:32.050 --> 00:05:36.070
of the telegraph and he develops
kind of a newspaper sales

00:05:36.070 --> 00:05:38.980
scheme during the
Civil War where

00:05:38.980 --> 00:05:43.600
he gets the newspapers
ahead of time in Cleveland,

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:46.960
gets them out to the trains
coming into Cleveland,

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:48.850
and then sells
them on the trains.

00:05:48.850 --> 00:05:50.912
And he's kind of kept--

00:05:50.912 --> 00:05:52.870
in other words, he kind
of beats the news cycle

00:05:52.870 --> 00:05:56.470
and then unloads newspapers on
these early commuting efforts

00:05:56.470 --> 00:05:59.500
as people are coming
into the city.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:03.400
He gets his big
break by scooping up

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:06.250
the child of the
telegraph operator.

00:06:06.250 --> 00:06:08.890
So trains had to operate
by telegraph systems--

00:06:08.890 --> 00:06:12.190
they were a crucial technology
to enable trains to work.

00:06:12.190 --> 00:06:17.700
And the telegraph operator for a
train system is very important,

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:20.790
but also obviously serves a
larger community communications

00:06:20.790 --> 00:06:21.810
purpose.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:24.270
So the kid of the
telegraph operator

00:06:24.270 --> 00:06:25.860
is down on the tracks--

00:06:25.860 --> 00:06:28.080
train is coming down the tracks.

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.190
Edison, as a boy,
sees what's happening,

00:06:31.190 --> 00:06:35.155
rushes, scoops the child up,
barely escapes the train.

00:06:35.155 --> 00:06:36.780
Needless to say, the
telegraph operator

00:06:36.780 --> 00:06:41.610
is appreciative, so he
trains Edison in Morse code

00:06:41.610 --> 00:06:44.130
and how telegraph
operations work.

00:06:44.130 --> 00:06:46.980
So he becomes an expert on
telegraph, which is obviously

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:50.130
early electrical technology.

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:53.190
And he becomes a master
at it, and then he

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:55.080
becomes very interested
in technology itself.

00:06:55.080 --> 00:06:57.180
So over time, he
goes to New York--

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:59.370
he develops what
becomes, in effect,

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:01.530
an early stock
ticker, which can--

00:07:01.530 --> 00:07:03.060
what we would call multiplex.

00:07:03.060 --> 00:07:06.330
In other words, you could
receive multiple telegraphing

00:07:06.330 --> 00:07:10.050
signals and communications
over the same line, which

00:07:10.050 --> 00:07:13.500
obviously was a key enabler
for keeping track of stocks.

00:07:13.500 --> 00:07:18.390
So he becomes very close to
the scions of Wall Street,

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:19.590
including JP Morgan.

00:07:19.590 --> 00:07:23.730
He gets to know them all
because he's like their enabler.

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:28.300
And then he sees this thing
in Ansonia Connecticut.

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:31.840
It's not-- it's a much
bigger version of this,

00:07:31.840 --> 00:07:34.780
but there's this
kind of gimmick--

00:07:34.780 --> 00:07:41.190
these nine foot tall
polls with a spark,

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:43.260
because they're
positive and negative

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:44.910
a spark travels across--

00:07:44.910 --> 00:07:46.743
looks really cool.

00:07:46.743 --> 00:07:48.160
People are wondering
around-- they

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:49.910
don't know what to do
with it, but they're

00:07:49.910 --> 00:07:54.630
awestruck by this kind of
electric movement of lightning

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:56.520
going across the two poles.

00:07:56.520 --> 00:08:01.110
Edison has the idea-- oh, light.

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:05.020
So he takes the-- he makes
his money on Wall Street,

00:08:05.020 --> 00:08:06.750
he takes all his money out.

00:08:06.750 --> 00:08:10.320
He goes off into a farm
in Menlo Park, New Jersey

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:13.510
out into this rural area.

00:08:13.510 --> 00:08:18.790
He hires this team which
consists of an interesting mix

00:08:18.790 --> 00:08:20.080
of artisans--

00:08:20.080 --> 00:08:24.910
like, there's an incredibly
important glass blower here,

00:08:24.910 --> 00:08:27.490
which heralds back to the
MIT glass lab which I always

00:08:27.490 --> 00:08:28.930
buy stuff from.

00:08:28.930 --> 00:08:32.620
And there's also
scientists and engineers

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:34.750
in here, but a lot
of people who just

00:08:34.750 --> 00:08:37.270
know how to do things
who are very good at sort

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:39.850
of mechanical tinkering.

00:08:39.850 --> 00:08:42.580
And it's an interesting
team, and he

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:45.190
has to take this idea
of this weird arc

00:08:45.190 --> 00:08:47.650
that he saw-- these nine
foot tall couple of poles

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:49.680
that he saw in
Ansonia Connecticut

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:50.930
and turn it into a light bulb.

00:08:50.930 --> 00:08:56.273
It's not an easy job
and it's very intense.

00:08:56.273 --> 00:08:57.940
There's only a certain
amount of money--

00:08:57.940 --> 00:08:59.380
the money is going to run out.

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:03.550
He's gotta get this thing done
before he runs out of cash.

00:09:03.550 --> 00:09:08.610
And they work
literally all the time.

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:13.380
They're always on it but they're
having the time of their lives.

00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:16.110
So there's a wood
stove in here over in--

00:09:16.110 --> 00:09:19.140
I'm not sure-- maybe
it's in another corner.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:23.490
But around midnight, they all
gather around the wood stove

00:09:23.490 --> 00:09:24.290
and they're--

00:09:24.290 --> 00:09:26.860
rap music has not
been invented yet,

00:09:26.860 --> 00:09:33.360
so they do doggerel verses which
they throw at one another--

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:36.450
insulting and funny and
this incredible doggerel

00:09:36.450 --> 00:09:38.700
verse back and forth going on.

00:09:38.700 --> 00:09:42.360
And they all have big cherry
pies and apple pies at midnight

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:45.390
and gather around the stove.

00:09:45.390 --> 00:09:47.670
It's a very intense effort.

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:50.880
And actually, Edison
is away for so long

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.127
from the farmhouse which is
further back on the property

00:09:54.127 --> 00:09:56.460
that at one point, when he
comes in at like 2:00 o'clock

00:09:56.460 --> 00:09:58.440
in the morning, his wife
pulls a revolver on him

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:00.065
thinking he's an
intruder because she's

00:10:00.065 --> 00:10:01.850
seen him so rarely.

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:04.080
Fortunately, she doesn't shoot.

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.840
But there they are gathered
on the idea factory,

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:12.330
and eventually they come
up with the core concepts.

00:10:12.330 --> 00:10:14.550
The vacuum tube
obviously is core here

00:10:14.550 --> 00:10:16.380
and the right
filament is core here.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:19.860
They come up with a working
model of the electric light.

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:21.420
There's only one problem--

00:10:21.420 --> 00:10:23.910
there's no electrical system.

00:10:23.910 --> 00:10:25.717
There's no nothing.

00:10:25.717 --> 00:10:27.300
So they've got a
wonderful application

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:29.220
for a nonexistent system.

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:35.510
So the real innovation here
is not simply the invention,

00:10:35.510 --> 00:10:38.570
it's creating the whole system.

00:10:38.570 --> 00:10:40.850
So they have to envision--

00:10:40.850 --> 00:10:43.880
they have to think of what
an electric utility might be.

00:10:43.880 --> 00:10:46.970
They envision the
utility, they envision

00:10:46.970 --> 00:10:48.620
what a generator would be.

00:10:48.620 --> 00:10:50.690
They have to think through
all these early safety

00:10:50.690 --> 00:10:52.610
requirements.

00:10:52.610 --> 00:10:56.660
So it's an incredibly big
thing that they're launching.

00:10:56.660 --> 00:10:59.120
They're launching the
electrical system, not simply

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:00.380
the light bulb.

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:01.880
But the light bulb
is the enabler

00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:04.760
that's going to enable
them to sell the system.

00:11:04.760 --> 00:11:06.440
Eventually, they do
a big demonstration

00:11:06.440 --> 00:11:10.160
on a couple of city blocks in
New York-- everybody loves it.

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:11.630
Gas lighting is
not what you call

00:11:11.630 --> 00:11:14.690
optimal since you have a good
chance of blowing yourself up.

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:17.950
And the nation
eventually switches over,

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:21.380
but I just wanted you to
see what that innovation

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:23.313
moment looks like.

00:11:23.313 --> 00:11:24.980
And we'll talk about
great group theory,

00:11:24.980 --> 00:11:27.230
and this is certainly
a great group.

00:11:27.230 --> 00:11:32.313
But that's the moment
we're after in this class.

00:11:32.313 --> 00:11:33.980
That's the moment we
want to understand.

00:11:33.980 --> 00:11:38.420
We want to understand how
that innovation emerges

00:11:38.420 --> 00:11:42.410
from the group, but
importantly, how it scales--

00:11:42.410 --> 00:11:43.940
what happens to it.

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:45.510
So that's kind of a little--

00:11:45.510 --> 00:11:47.310
that's story time
for today's class.

00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:51.080
Now we'll do serious work.

00:11:51.080 --> 00:11:53.100
I want to get some
other basic ideas down.

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:55.430
So we talked about some
basic concepts last time.

00:11:55.430 --> 00:11:57.290
I want to put a few
more on the table.

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:04.180
Steps in the technology
development process.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:07.060
So we talked a
little bit last week

00:12:07.060 --> 00:12:11.690
about three of those
steps, but let me put them

00:12:11.690 --> 00:12:13.030
into a larger context.

00:12:13.030 --> 00:12:15.370
So typically,
you're going to have

00:12:15.370 --> 00:12:18.760
to go through a
series of steps here

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:22.930
to actually get to really
scaling a technology up.

00:12:22.930 --> 00:12:26.140
We talked last week
about having a vision.

00:12:26.140 --> 00:12:28.990
We talked last week
about supporting

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.960
enabling technologies.

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:34.930
Then you're going to do
your particular invention.

00:12:34.930 --> 00:12:37.720
Idea-- you're going to need to
do some research to perfect it.

00:12:37.720 --> 00:12:40.305
You're going to need to
develop a prototype of it.

00:12:40.305 --> 00:12:42.430
Then you're going to need
to go through engineering

00:12:42.430 --> 00:12:44.200
development.

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:46.360
Then you can start to
think about production,

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:48.430
and manufacturing that
prototype, and then

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:51.260
eventually scaling up to
commercial production.

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:54.730
You've got to have a supporting
infrastructure system

00:12:54.730 --> 00:12:57.640
and there may be additional
applications that you

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:59.795
can use and pile on here.

00:12:59.795 --> 00:13:02.170
And then you've got to go
through a series of generations

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:03.420
of the product.

00:13:03.420 --> 00:13:07.590
So that's a lot of
stuff to get through.

00:13:07.590 --> 00:13:14.050
So the US typically thinks
about innovation as, like,

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:17.790
in the vision idea
research realm,

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:20.850
but it's a much
more complex process

00:13:20.850 --> 00:13:25.290
that has to be mastered to
actually get from the discovery

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:28.480
to the innovation.

00:13:28.480 --> 00:13:30.810
So there's models for
technology change,

00:13:30.810 --> 00:13:32.940
and we'll talk more about
those in a later class,

00:13:32.940 --> 00:13:37.890
but just a couple of core ideas
to put on the table right now.

00:13:37.890 --> 00:13:43.560
Technology push-- so we talked
a bit about the innovation

00:13:43.560 --> 00:13:46.650
pipeline last week.

00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:51.990
Technology push is typically
where you support research,

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:55.200
something emerges from
that research in effect,

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:59.670
and then enters into
widespread use--

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:01.890
typically a
commercializable product.

00:14:01.890 --> 00:14:04.680
So in effect, you're nurturing
and developing a technology,

00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:09.120
and you're pushing it
towards the economy.

00:14:09.120 --> 00:14:12.390
Technology pull, or
sometimes called demand pull,

00:14:12.390 --> 00:14:14.410
is a different model.

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:19.530
So in this case, the market
will create an opportunity.

00:14:19.530 --> 00:14:22.260
The market may create
a niche or someone

00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:24.690
may spot the opportunity
or the niche.

00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:27.390
And in effect, the
market is going

00:14:27.390 --> 00:14:29.510
to pull that technology out--

00:14:29.510 --> 00:14:32.310
is going to be, in
a way, the enabler

00:14:32.310 --> 00:14:34.320
for that technology to evolve.

00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:37.310
So these are two very
different processes,

00:14:37.310 --> 00:14:40.090
and we'll talk more
about who does which.

00:14:40.090 --> 00:14:43.670
There's incremental innovation
and there's radical innovation.

00:14:43.670 --> 00:14:47.790
So incremental innovation--
as a definition here,

00:14:47.790 --> 00:14:50.070
it improves function,
aesthetics, performance,

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:53.350
efficiency, manufacturability
and so forth.

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:57.540
In other words, modest
incremental steps.

00:14:57.540 --> 00:15:00.030
It's very important.

00:15:00.030 --> 00:15:03.000
We all kind of love
radical innovation,

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:06.420
and there's actually
good evidence

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:10.080
that radical innovation
will lead to a really

00:15:10.080 --> 00:15:13.440
disproportionate profit impact.

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.620
In other words, if you can
launch a radical innovation,

00:15:16.620 --> 00:15:19.297
the gains can really
be big, and that

00:15:19.297 --> 00:15:21.630
will become an important idea
when we talk about venture

00:15:21.630 --> 00:15:23.270
capital later in the class.

