00:20:35.008 --> 00:20:36.550
In other words, it's
able to continue

00:20:36.550 --> 00:20:40.630
to do pretty radical innovations
on a continuing basis.

00:20:40.630 --> 00:20:43.360
What enables a company to keep--

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:46.390
that ability to keep innovating.

00:20:46.390 --> 00:20:49.540
Because it's not--
there are only

00:20:49.540 --> 00:20:52.180
a handful of companies in the
world that are over 100 years

00:20:52.180 --> 00:20:54.220
old.

00:20:54.220 --> 00:20:57.970
They burn themselves out.

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:00.310
Globalization obviously
spurs competitiveness,

00:21:00.310 --> 00:21:04.210
and it spurs entry and
increased competition.

00:21:04.210 --> 00:21:07.150
It speeds the
product cycle, so it

00:21:07.150 --> 00:21:11.650
can be disruptive of this
traditional product cycle.

00:21:11.650 --> 00:21:14.920
There may be-- and we'll talk
about it more in our next

00:21:14.920 --> 00:21:15.530
class--

00:21:15.530 --> 00:21:19.660
but a kind of rebirth
of manufacturing process

00:21:19.660 --> 00:21:24.880
improvements that could disrupt
this cycle and change it.

00:21:24.880 --> 00:21:29.150
And there's now a very
interesting service sector

00:21:29.150 --> 00:21:32.030
that's not hard-product
based that's emerging,

00:21:32.030 --> 00:21:36.940
and the possibility of
tying services to hardware.

00:21:36.940 --> 00:21:41.650
So an Apple iPhone
is a classic example

00:21:41.650 --> 00:21:46.252
of a hard technology that is
also a service delivery model.

00:21:46.252 --> 00:21:47.710
So we're getting
these combinations

00:21:47.710 --> 00:21:50.260
in interesting new ways.

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.990
That will change this
product cycle as well.

00:21:53.990 --> 00:21:57.700
So it's not a eternal, but I
want you to get an idea product

00:21:57.700 --> 00:21:59.790
cycle theory.

00:21:59.790 --> 00:22:04.290
And then our final idea before
we dig in on the readings--

00:22:04.290 --> 00:22:08.260
dynamic versus static
competitive advantage.

00:22:08.260 --> 00:22:13.230
So David Ricardo, great
economist in the 19th century,

00:22:13.230 --> 00:22:18.660
develops essentially a theory
of static comparative advantage.

00:22:18.660 --> 00:22:21.240
That advantage would be
intrinsic to a country

00:22:21.240 --> 00:22:23.520
typically based on
natural resources,

00:22:23.520 --> 00:22:28.620
and his famous
economic example was--

00:22:28.620 --> 00:22:33.120
and we talked about it
a little bit last week--

00:22:33.120 --> 00:22:37.320
but England has a lot of
rain, has a lot of grass--

00:22:37.320 --> 00:22:41.730
it can have sheep, it
can do wool very well.

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:44.130
And Portugal doesn't have
that much rain, doesn't

00:22:44.130 --> 00:22:47.880
have that much grass, but
it's great for growing grapes,

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:51.810
so it's going to do
wine, England will wool.

00:22:51.810 --> 00:22:54.120
Each has a natural
comparative advantage

00:22:54.120 --> 00:23:01.140
based on a resource advantage
and it benefits both to trade.

00:23:01.140 --> 00:23:03.180
Portugal expands
its market for wine

00:23:03.180 --> 00:23:04.920
by growing outside
its own borders.

00:23:04.920 --> 00:23:06.720
England expands
its market for wool

00:23:06.720 --> 00:23:08.340
by growing outside its borders.

00:23:08.340 --> 00:23:10.060
There's a benefit to each.

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:13.530
So that's the kind of 19th
century concept that's

00:23:13.530 --> 00:23:17.370
the heart of free trade theory.

00:23:17.370 --> 00:23:20.340
That's a static
comparative advantage.

00:23:20.340 --> 00:23:22.500
Starting around the middle
of the 20th century,

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:25.200
something very different
began to evolve.

00:23:25.200 --> 00:23:30.240
A dynamic comparative
advantage, and this

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:31.930
is based on growth theory.

00:23:31.930 --> 00:23:35.160
In other words, if
you can be innovative

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:36.930
and you can lead
innovation waves,

00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:39.660
you can capture a lot of the
early gains of that innovation

00:23:39.660 --> 00:23:41.010
wave.

00:23:41.010 --> 00:23:44.550
It's Solow innovation
based growth theory.

00:23:44.550 --> 00:23:49.140
So that is a dynamic
advantage created by--

00:23:49.140 --> 00:23:52.050
and we have to understand the
menu-- but investments in R&D,

00:23:52.050 --> 00:23:54.360
and education, and
efficient governance,

00:23:54.360 --> 00:23:56.930
those could all be inputs--

00:23:56.930 --> 00:23:59.400
and we'll talk more about
the system later today--

00:23:59.400 --> 00:24:03.930
into a dynamic
comparative advantage.

00:24:03.930 --> 00:24:08.130
Now a dynamic comparative
advantage is not eternal--

00:24:08.130 --> 00:24:08.970
it may get lost.

00:24:08.970 --> 00:24:10.595
And we're going to
talk about some work

00:24:10.595 --> 00:24:15.410
by Paul Samuelson who laid
a lot of that thinking out

00:24:15.410 --> 00:24:20.710
in a famous 2004 article in one
of the next couple of classes.

00:24:20.710 --> 00:24:26.070
So the US created, in many
ways, the biggest innovating

00:24:26.070 --> 00:24:30.840
economy in the world coming out
of that World War II period.

00:24:30.840 --> 00:24:34.860
So it built a
competitive advantage

00:24:34.860 --> 00:24:42.237
based on innovation, which
had been evolving in Europe.

00:24:42.237 --> 00:24:43.820
And countries like
Britain and Germany

00:24:43.820 --> 00:24:46.700
had been doing something
similar starting

00:24:46.700 --> 00:24:48.920
in the second half
of the 19th century,

00:24:48.920 --> 00:24:51.860
but the US really scaled that
model up and really built

00:24:51.860 --> 00:24:55.850
a very strong early
stage innovation system.

00:24:55.850 --> 00:24:58.700
It became the richest
nation on earth.

00:24:58.700 --> 00:25:01.610
That was its model, that was
its comparative advantage.

00:25:01.610 --> 00:25:06.200
Now the problem with a
comparative advantage

00:25:06.200 --> 00:25:09.410
based on innovation
is that others

00:25:09.410 --> 00:25:10.950
can figure out how to innovate.

00:25:14.420 --> 00:25:17.090
England is always going to
have rain, and sheep, and wool,

00:25:17.090 --> 00:25:21.980
and Portugal is always going to
have sun, and grapes, and wine.

00:25:21.980 --> 00:25:24.860
Those are inherent, static
comparative advantages--

00:25:24.860 --> 00:25:26.190
they are not going to change.

00:25:26.190 --> 00:25:29.570
An innovation
advantage can change.

00:25:29.570 --> 00:25:33.050
So the US had an incredible mass
production system coming out

00:25:33.050 --> 00:25:34.820
of the end of World War II.

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:37.700
Japan figures out a
better innovation model

00:25:37.700 --> 00:25:42.710
based on quality production
and takes consumer electronics

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:44.960
and large parts of
the auto sector.

00:25:44.960 --> 00:25:50.990
So that's how a comparative
innovation advantage can erode.

00:25:50.990 --> 00:25:55.430
So it's powerful-- you can
get very rich as a nation

00:25:55.430 --> 00:25:57.330
and as a society--

00:25:57.330 --> 00:26:01.010
but it's also up for grabs.

