01:00:02.370 --> 01:00:04.550
So in last week's
class, we talked

01:00:04.550 --> 01:00:06.350
about these direct
innovation factors.

01:00:06.350 --> 01:00:09.590
In other words, these factors
that you really can't do

01:00:09.590 --> 01:00:12.440
without if you want to have
a strong innovation system.

01:00:12.440 --> 01:00:14.930
And the purpose of that would
be to drive economic growth,

01:00:14.930 --> 01:00:19.310
to grow economic well-being in
your society in your economy.

01:00:19.310 --> 01:00:27.620
So government plays a role in
some of these direct factors.

01:00:27.620 --> 01:00:32.230
It supports almost
all of university R&D,

01:00:32.230 --> 01:00:34.310
it supports governmental
laboratories,

01:00:34.310 --> 01:00:38.270
it provides lots of support
for the education system.

01:00:38.270 --> 01:00:43.950
And then it provides support
for industry R&D in some areas--

01:00:43.950 --> 01:00:47.310
particularly defense, but to
some extent in agriculture.

01:00:47.310 --> 01:00:48.770
So those are kind of--

01:00:48.770 --> 01:00:58.170
if the Solow factor of
doing R&D is a core factor,

01:00:58.170 --> 01:01:00.080
then you can see the
governmental role here.

01:01:00.080 --> 01:01:02.180
But there's also a private
sector and industry

01:01:02.180 --> 01:01:05.990
role on that initial factor.

01:01:05.990 --> 01:01:08.600
Of course, there's industry
R&D which, as we discussed,

01:01:08.600 --> 01:01:12.530
is predominantly D, but
that's what takes you

01:01:12.530 --> 01:01:15.590
through the prototyping, and
engineering, and production

01:01:15.590 --> 01:01:16.670
stages.

01:01:16.670 --> 01:01:19.160
And then industry provides
the dominant role in training.

01:01:22.320 --> 01:01:28.280
So those are direct
Solow-Romer factors

01:01:28.280 --> 01:01:32.000
that are tied to industry and
tied to the private sector.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:37.520
But then there is
a raft of indirect,

01:01:37.520 --> 01:01:42.180
or we could call them
implicit, innovation factors.

01:01:42.180 --> 01:01:47.030
So if Nelson is right that there
is an innovation ecosystem,

01:01:47.030 --> 01:01:51.440
then there's a lot of pieces
in that complex system.

01:01:51.440 --> 01:01:55.220
And government is supplying
some of those pieces that

01:01:55.220 --> 01:01:57.980
have a role in the
innovation process,

01:01:57.980 --> 01:02:01.430
but are not as direct as the
first thing we talked about.

01:02:01.430 --> 01:02:06.735
So government is providing
fiscal tax monetary policy,

01:02:06.735 --> 01:02:09.530
it's providing trade policy,
technology standards,

01:02:09.530 --> 01:02:12.307
technology transfer policies.

01:02:12.307 --> 01:02:13.890
It's providing
government procurement,

01:02:13.890 --> 01:02:17.030
which buys a lot of technology,
particularly in defense.

01:02:17.030 --> 01:02:19.220
It sets up the intellectual
property system,

01:02:19.220 --> 01:02:23.570
the whole legal contracting
liability system,

01:02:23.570 --> 01:02:27.110
the regulatory system
in many, many areas,

01:02:27.110 --> 01:02:30.420
accounting standards,
export controls.

01:02:30.420 --> 01:02:34.430
These all will have an effect
on the innovation system

01:02:34.430 --> 01:02:38.240
and your ability to innovate.

01:02:38.240 --> 01:02:41.150
But then there are
these indirect factors

01:02:41.150 --> 01:02:45.020
that are is less critical than
the two we've talked about,

01:02:45.020 --> 01:02:47.420
but nonetheless
part of that system.

01:02:47.420 --> 01:02:50.090
So the private sector sets
some really important ones.

01:02:50.090 --> 01:02:52.790
That includes investment
capital which can be angel,

01:02:52.790 --> 01:02:58.240
or venture, or IPO, or
equity, or lending markets--

01:02:58.240 --> 01:03:00.560
is a private sector
function obviously.

01:03:00.560 --> 01:03:02.390
Management and
management organization

01:03:02.390 --> 01:03:05.030
is really a private sector
function in our system.

01:03:05.030 --> 01:03:06.640
The whole reward system--

01:03:06.640 --> 01:03:09.590
the compensation
system for talent

01:03:09.590 --> 01:03:11.630
is largely private sector set.

01:03:11.630 --> 01:03:14.440
So the private sector
plays a huge role too

01:03:14.440 --> 01:03:17.120
in this complex ecosystem mix.

01:03:17.120 --> 01:03:23.250
So the picture I want you to
have is of a complex innovation

01:03:23.250 --> 01:03:24.690
system.

01:03:24.690 --> 01:03:28.090
There's direct factors,
and if we include Nelson,

01:03:28.090 --> 01:03:30.990
we've talked about three.

01:03:30.990 --> 01:03:33.060
But there's a whole mix
of other stuff there,

01:03:33.060 --> 01:03:35.820
and you want to get as many of
those right in your innovation

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:39.030
system as you can to have a
strong functioning innovation

01:03:39.030 --> 01:03:40.210
system.

01:03:40.210 --> 01:03:42.810
So it's not only the actors.

01:03:42.810 --> 01:03:46.290
You've also got to take into
account this larger system

01:03:46.290 --> 01:03:47.580
as well.

01:03:47.580 --> 01:03:52.560
And we'll get, in a
few minutes, into some

01:03:52.560 --> 01:03:55.355
of the indirect factors
and how to look at those.

01:03:55.355 --> 01:03:57.480
But first we're going to
do innovation wave theory.

01:03:57.480 --> 01:04:00.490
That's Rob Atkinson
who's head of ITIF,

01:04:00.490 --> 01:04:04.290
a thinktank in Washington.

01:04:04.290 --> 01:04:07.530
We talked about-- and I
drew a scribble last week

01:04:07.530 --> 01:04:11.550
on the blackboard, but this
is a better rendition--

01:04:11.550 --> 01:04:13.420
what does an innovation
wave look like?

01:04:13.420 --> 01:04:17.110
And just to recap from
our discussion last week,

01:04:17.110 --> 01:04:20.580
there's a long build up
and that can be 15, 20

01:04:20.580 --> 01:04:22.973
years-- it can be longer.

01:04:22.973 --> 01:04:24.640
And then at some
point, it hits a moment

01:04:24.640 --> 01:04:26.790
where it can start to
scale up pretty quickly

01:04:26.790 --> 01:04:29.620
and spread into the
society and economy.

01:04:29.620 --> 01:04:32.430
So there is a fast
growth period here--

01:04:32.430 --> 01:04:35.177
maybe that's a decade.

01:04:35.177 --> 01:04:36.760
Then there's a period
of more stable--

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:39.990
there's always a
bubble and then there's

01:04:39.990 --> 01:04:42.930
a period of more stable growth.

01:04:42.930 --> 01:04:45.420
And maybe that's 20
years, maybe that's more.

01:04:45.420 --> 01:04:50.070
And then eventually, you reach
kind of technological maturity.

01:04:50.070 --> 01:04:55.050
So the IT wave, the one you all
are most familiar with that's

01:04:55.050 --> 01:04:58.680
still ongoing, long build up.

01:04:58.680 --> 01:05:00.160
When do we start it from?

01:05:00.160 --> 01:05:03.330
Do we start it from
Babbage, do we start it

01:05:03.330 --> 01:05:04.890
from Vannevar
Bush's differential

01:05:04.890 --> 01:05:09.210
analyzer in the 1930s, do
we start it from ENIAC--

01:05:09.210 --> 01:05:14.790
1946, the first functioning
mainframe computer.

01:05:14.790 --> 01:05:16.290
We can start it
at various points,

01:05:16.290 --> 01:05:18.660
but you get a sense for
how long that buildup is.

01:05:18.660 --> 01:05:21.540
And then finally,
we hit the 1990s

01:05:21.540 --> 01:05:24.140
and that incredible decade
of growth in the 1990s.

01:05:24.140 --> 01:05:26.560
This very rapid scale up.

