01:07:36.210 --> 01:07:39.450
I mean, there's-- we could call
them black swan elements that

01:07:39.450 --> 01:07:42.105
pop up periodically that
disrupt everything like crazy.

01:07:44.610 --> 01:07:46.650
I'd argue that
you could actually

01:07:46.650 --> 01:07:54.140
treat the growth in financial
services as an innovation wave.

01:07:54.140 --> 01:07:57.480
That there were a whole
series of technological areas

01:07:57.480 --> 01:07:58.620
of advance--

01:07:58.620 --> 01:08:02.370
in areas like mathematics
in particular.

01:08:02.370 --> 01:08:04.470
But IT revolution
accompanies that.

01:08:04.470 --> 01:08:06.540
You could actually add
the technology foundation

01:08:06.540 --> 01:08:09.390
and the processes
to really create

01:08:09.390 --> 01:08:13.050
global financial
services system.

01:08:13.050 --> 01:08:17.010
And you can plot that
growth, and sure enough, they

01:08:17.010 --> 01:08:18.710
have a bubble.

01:08:18.710 --> 01:08:22.290
The problem with the bubble
in the financial services bust

01:08:22.290 --> 01:08:25.290
is that it just doesn't bring
down a bunch of dot-coms,

01:08:25.290 --> 01:08:26.819
it brings down the
entire economy.

01:08:26.819 --> 01:08:30.660
So be careful about innovation
waves in the financial services

01:08:30.660 --> 01:08:33.960
sector-- be very careful
because it messes everything up.

01:08:33.960 --> 01:08:35.540
But I think you can actually--

01:08:35.540 --> 01:08:37.290
I think that one
actually works as a wave.

01:08:37.290 --> 01:08:39.109
Biotech for sure
works as a wave.

01:08:39.109 --> 01:08:42.010
It's not nearly as big as IT,
but nonetheless is significant.

01:08:42.010 --> 01:08:42.510
Matt?

01:08:42.510 --> 01:08:46.540
AUDIENCE: I think my impression
of that, reading Atkinson,

01:08:46.540 --> 01:08:49.350
was that because the
timescale of the innovation

01:08:49.350 --> 01:08:53.140
is so much longer than
the business cycle,

01:08:53.140 --> 01:08:55.680
the business cycles are, like,
flips that are superimposed

01:08:55.680 --> 01:08:56.180
[INAUDIBLE].

01:08:56.180 --> 01:08:57.788
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
Very good point.

01:08:57.788 --> 01:08:59.205
They modulate
through the process.

01:09:01.710 --> 01:09:03.990
Atkinson argues
that in US history,

01:09:03.990 --> 01:09:06.270
there were essentially
four phases--

01:09:06.270 --> 01:09:10.740
for long waves in
the US economy.

01:09:10.740 --> 01:09:12.257
So he argues that--

01:09:12.257 --> 01:09:14.340
and different people can
look at this differently.

01:09:14.340 --> 01:09:16.548
And look, there's big waves,
and there's small waves,

01:09:16.548 --> 01:09:18.540
and there's wavelets
within a wave,

01:09:18.540 --> 01:09:21.000
so it's not absolutely
straightforward.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:23.640
But he argues that in the
1840s, the development

01:09:23.640 --> 01:09:26.910
of small local manufacturing
industries in New

01:09:26.910 --> 01:09:31.319
England around textiles
and early machines,

01:09:31.319 --> 01:09:33.359
that's one wave.

01:09:33.359 --> 01:09:37.859
By the 1880s and '90s, that's
regional factory based systems.

01:09:37.859 --> 01:09:40.830
And you know what those
19th century cities look

01:09:40.830 --> 01:09:44.310
like-- think about Pittsburgh.

01:09:44.310 --> 01:09:46.500
By the 1940s, we're
moving towards

01:09:46.500 --> 01:09:49.140
corporate mass
production in areas

01:09:49.140 --> 01:09:51.660
like automobiles and aircraft.

01:09:51.660 --> 01:09:55.530
Then in the 1990s, he
argues the new economy

01:09:55.530 --> 01:10:01.570
which is an IT based
innovation wave emerges--

01:10:01.570 --> 01:10:04.410
that's global, that's
entrepreneurial,

01:10:04.410 --> 01:10:05.380
that's knowledge based.

01:10:05.380 --> 01:10:11.680
But that's his way of looking
at innovation waves in the US

01:10:11.680 --> 01:10:12.624
economy.

01:10:15.220 --> 01:10:18.940
We're familiar with the 1990s--
we just discussed that one,

01:10:18.940 --> 01:10:21.610
so I won't dwell on it here.

01:10:21.610 --> 01:10:23.290
The political
system typically is

01:10:23.290 --> 01:10:25.630
slow to react to these
innovation waves.

01:10:25.630 --> 01:10:28.630
It does not see them.

01:10:28.630 --> 01:10:31.420
John Maynard Keynes,
the great economist

01:10:31.420 --> 01:10:35.190
who created Keynesian
theory, once

01:10:35.190 --> 01:10:37.260
said, "practical men
who believe themselves

01:10:37.260 --> 01:10:40.530
to be quite exempt from
any intellectual influences

01:10:40.530 --> 01:10:44.310
are usually slaves of
some defunct economist."

01:10:44.310 --> 01:10:46.830
In other words, they're
operating off old economics

01:10:46.830 --> 01:10:50.310
and tend to perpetrate them.

01:10:50.310 --> 01:10:54.330
Atkinson argues that
the American old left

01:10:54.330 --> 01:10:56.370
was focused essentially
on a mass production

01:10:56.370 --> 01:11:00.300
economy, which had been
eclipsed by the time the IT

01:11:00.300 --> 01:11:02.020
wave emerges.

01:11:02.020 --> 01:11:05.430
The conservative
political elements--

01:11:05.430 --> 01:11:08.640
the Republican Party at the
time and he's writing in--

01:11:08.640 --> 01:11:13.090
was very supply side,
classical economics based.

01:11:13.090 --> 01:11:14.790
They were worried
about capital supply,

01:11:14.790 --> 01:11:16.207
and they were
worried particularly

01:11:16.207 --> 01:11:19.740
about marginal tax rates
affecting that capital supply.

01:11:19.740 --> 01:11:22.680
So that wasn't organized
around an innovation wave.

01:11:22.680 --> 01:11:26.370
That was organized around
old classical economics.

01:11:26.370 --> 01:11:30.210
So in a way, both
parties got organized

01:11:30.210 --> 01:11:34.580
around the two fundamental bases
in classical economic theory.

01:11:34.580 --> 01:11:36.930
The Democratic Party around
a broad definition of labor

01:11:36.930 --> 01:11:39.180
supply that includes education,
and health, and things

01:11:39.180 --> 01:11:41.070
like that, and the
Republican Party

01:11:41.070 --> 01:11:43.240
around a theory
of capital supply,

01:11:43.240 --> 01:11:45.390
which was translated
into tax policy.

01:11:45.390 --> 01:11:47.430
It's largely where
those parties are today.

01:11:47.430 --> 01:11:50.520
They missed innovation
based growth theory.

01:11:50.520 --> 01:11:52.800
AUDIENCE: When did that start?

01:11:52.800 --> 01:11:57.063
When did that
happen [INAUDIBLE]??

01:11:57.063 --> 01:11:59.230
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: I would
say that the parties had

01:11:59.230 --> 01:12:03.430
locked into this by pretty
early on in the 20th century.

01:12:03.430 --> 01:12:05.395
By the time of
Franklin Roosevelt

01:12:05.395 --> 01:12:07.985
is when the Democratic
Party locks into--

01:12:07.985 --> 01:12:10.360
look, there's nothing wrong
with capitalist [INAUDIBLE]..

01:12:10.360 --> 01:12:12.683
There's nothing wrong
with labor supply.

01:12:12.683 --> 01:12:15.100
They're important elements and
they need to be considered,

01:12:15.100 --> 01:12:16.720
and they're contributors.

01:12:16.720 --> 01:12:20.920
We just know, however, that
innovation based growth

01:12:20.920 --> 01:12:25.930
is the larger factor in growth,
and the political parties

01:12:25.930 --> 01:12:27.950
haven't gotten there yet.

01:12:27.950 --> 01:12:32.320
So a real structural
problem in the US system.

01:12:32.320 --> 01:12:37.470
Neither then embrace
growth economics

01:12:37.470 --> 01:12:41.440
and spurring innovation,
and that leads us

01:12:41.440 --> 01:12:46.240
to some interesting ideas
about social organization.

01:12:46.240 --> 01:12:51.110
So technology and
technological organization

01:12:51.110 --> 01:12:56.330
is going to drive social
and economic structures.

01:12:56.330 --> 01:12:59.420
So it's a really important
point that he raises here,

01:12:59.420 --> 01:13:01.760
and it's I think
one of the reasons

01:13:01.760 --> 01:13:06.680
why the subject of this class
is actually really important.

01:13:06.680 --> 01:13:09.800
It's bigger than standing
up cool technologies.

01:13:09.800 --> 01:13:14.990
It's a lot bigger than that
because this class is not only

01:13:14.990 --> 01:13:17.930
about technology
development, it is

01:13:17.930 --> 01:13:20.840
about the way society
organizes itself

01:13:20.840 --> 01:13:23.970
around those technologies.

01:13:23.970 --> 01:13:29.030
So Hagel, great German
philosopher-- "western society

01:13:29.030 --> 01:13:32.150
is driven by the
competition of ideas."

01:13:32.150 --> 01:13:35.270
Thesis, antithesis--
you all know the story.

01:13:35.270 --> 01:13:41.270
Marx introduces a very different
concept into that conversation.

01:13:41.270 --> 01:13:45.170
He argues that in acquiring
new productive forces,

01:13:45.170 --> 01:13:47.300
people change their
mode of production,

01:13:47.300 --> 01:13:49.340
and in changing their
mode of production,

01:13:49.340 --> 01:13:51.620
they change their way
of living and they

01:13:51.620 --> 01:13:54.830
change their social relations.

01:13:54.830 --> 01:13:58.010
So that's fundamental Marx
philosophical perspective.

01:13:58.010 --> 01:14:01.700
That is called
determinism in philosophy.

01:14:01.700 --> 01:14:05.060
In other words, the
technological order

01:14:05.060 --> 01:14:08.360
of your society will be
determinative of the kind

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:10.580
of society you have.

01:14:10.580 --> 01:14:12.290
And that's how Marxism evolves.

01:14:12.290 --> 01:14:14.840
That's the fundamental
philosophical underpinning.

01:14:14.840 --> 01:14:17.270
And he is seeing the
Industrial Revolution drive

01:14:17.270 --> 01:14:23.000
systematic change in
society in the late 18th

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:24.110
through the 19th century.

01:14:24.110 --> 01:14:25.550
That's what he's seeing.

01:14:25.550 --> 01:14:27.470
He's seeing this
incredible class order

01:14:27.470 --> 01:14:32.420
evolve to match the very
hierarchical structure

01:14:32.420 --> 01:14:35.450
that industrial organization,
driven by the Industrial

01:14:35.450 --> 01:14:37.625
Revolution, requires
at that time.

01:14:37.625 --> 01:14:39.535
Now, Stephanie,
you had a question?

01:14:39.535 --> 01:14:40.970
AUDIENCE: Yeah, [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:40.970 --> 01:14:42.600
I was wondering [INAUDIBLE]--

01:14:42.600 --> 01:14:44.132
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: I'll get it.

01:14:44.132 --> 01:14:46.090
AUDIENCE: --when I was
looking at the syllabus,

01:14:46.090 --> 01:14:48.396
was are we going to
talk about it some more?

01:14:48.396 --> 01:14:51.110
Because I guess I was
curious if you were operating

01:14:51.110 --> 01:14:53.690
under the presumption, at least
in the lecture and the ways

01:14:53.690 --> 01:14:55.460
in which we were supposed
to be perceiving readings

01:14:55.460 --> 01:14:56.085
were giving us.

01:14:56.085 --> 01:14:59.402
Like, capitalism is good, or
that capitalism is natural,

01:14:59.402 --> 01:15:03.194
or that capitalism is something
that technology sort of--

01:15:03.194 --> 01:15:06.350
or rather that capitalism
perpetuates technology,

01:15:06.350 --> 01:15:08.485
technology works to
perpetuate capitalism.

01:15:08.485 --> 01:15:10.610
When I think there's really
a lot of conversations,

01:15:10.610 --> 01:15:12.420
particularly arising
in the last maybe

01:15:12.420 --> 01:15:14.780
two or three years, about
the basic income guarantee

01:15:14.780 --> 01:15:17.090
and the potential for
technology really eliminating

01:15:17.090 --> 01:15:19.310
the necessity for labor
in [INAUDIBLE] economies.

01:15:19.310 --> 01:15:22.280
So I figured I would
ask at this point

01:15:22.280 --> 01:15:25.310
when it became relevant
because you had brought it up--

01:15:25.310 --> 01:15:26.150
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: [LAUGHS]
I gave you an opening.

01:15:26.150 --> 01:15:27.310
AUDIENCE: --there you go, yeah--

01:15:27.310 --> 01:15:28.950
whether or not we're operating
under the presumption

01:15:28.950 --> 01:15:31.550
that the free markets are good
or desirable in the long run.

01:15:33.337 --> 01:15:35.420
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: That
is really a big question.

01:15:35.420 --> 01:15:36.770
[LAUGHING]

01:15:36.770 --> 01:15:38.450
I guess I opened
myself up to that

01:15:38.450 --> 01:15:40.640
by bringing determinism in--

01:15:40.640 --> 01:15:44.750
using the excuse that
Atkinson raised the subject.

01:15:44.750 --> 01:15:47.150
Look, that's not a
dialogue that the US

01:15:47.150 --> 01:15:48.860
has had for some decades.

01:15:48.860 --> 01:15:53.180
We thought the Cold War was over
and we thought capitalism won.

01:15:53.180 --> 01:15:55.580
It's only in fairly recent
years that we're actually

01:15:55.580 --> 01:15:58.340
starting to think, hmm, maybe
there's some more elements here

01:15:58.340 --> 01:16:00.597
that we need to consider.

01:16:00.597 --> 01:16:02.180
Look, I think that's
an open question.

01:16:02.180 --> 01:16:04.160
Obviously, this class
is about innovation

01:16:04.160 --> 01:16:07.817
and it's about innovation in
largely capitalistic systems,

01:16:07.817 --> 01:16:10.400
which obviously is the direction
that the world economies have

01:16:10.400 --> 01:16:13.040
gone in worldwide.

01:16:13.040 --> 01:16:14.930
So I think that's the reality.

01:16:14.930 --> 01:16:18.570
That's the reality we have.

01:16:18.570 --> 01:16:23.390
My personal view is that
that's essentially a positive,

01:16:23.390 --> 01:16:25.490
but there are
different views here.

01:16:25.490 --> 01:16:30.380
And we have to keep in mind how
powerful the technologies that

01:16:30.380 --> 01:16:32.510
are coming out of these
innovation systems

01:16:32.510 --> 01:16:36.830
can be for how we relate
to one another as people--

01:16:36.830 --> 01:16:38.510
how we organize
our social lives.

01:16:42.230 --> 01:16:44.440
So the prevailing
technology system

01:16:44.440 --> 01:16:46.870
really sets parameters
on the fundamentals

01:16:46.870 --> 01:16:49.642
of social organization.

01:16:49.642 --> 01:16:51.640
A few other thoughts
along those lines--

01:16:51.640 --> 01:16:55.240
Kondratieff who developed the
fundamentals of wave theory

01:16:55.240 --> 01:16:57.010
back at the beginning
of the 20th century.

01:16:59.950 --> 01:17:07.870
He viewed depression as a
trough in a 50 year wave cycle.

01:17:07.870 --> 01:17:10.150
Classical economists'
view of depression

01:17:10.150 --> 01:17:13.120
was that they were waiting
for wages and prices

01:17:13.120 --> 01:17:17.980
to fall far enough
to enable a rebound.

01:17:17.980 --> 01:17:21.640
Eventually, everything is cheap
enough-- somebody will buy it.

01:17:21.640 --> 01:17:26.200
Keynes took on that attitude.

01:17:26.200 --> 01:17:29.170
This is to point back to
what you raised, Matt,

01:17:29.170 --> 01:17:33.310
about how does economic cycle
theory interact with innovation

01:17:33.310 --> 01:17:33.990
wave theories.

01:17:33.990 --> 01:17:37.720
So we're right exactly at
that point that you raised.

01:17:37.720 --> 01:17:39.970
So Keynes agreed,
but in the end he

01:17:39.970 --> 01:17:42.130
argued better intervene
because in the long range,

01:17:42.130 --> 01:17:43.390
we're all dead.

01:17:43.390 --> 01:17:45.400
So don't wait that long--

01:17:45.400 --> 01:17:47.950
better get on with it.

01:17:47.950 --> 01:17:52.570
Schumpeter definitely saw--
who's an advocate in economics

01:17:52.570 --> 01:17:56.230
of disruptive capitalism,
destructive capitalism--

01:17:56.230 --> 01:17:59.260
he saw Kondratieff's
long waves theory,

01:17:59.260 --> 01:18:01.990
but he saw them as driven
by innovation, not just

01:18:01.990 --> 01:18:04.568
in technology, but in
the accompanying aspects.

01:18:04.568 --> 01:18:05.860
So production and distribution.

01:18:05.860 --> 01:18:08.560
So it's not only the
technology, but it's

01:18:08.560 --> 01:18:10.420
the production and
distribution system too

01:18:10.420 --> 01:18:13.030
that he would add to that mix.

01:18:13.030 --> 01:18:15.760
So destructive
capitalism, in the end,

01:18:15.760 --> 01:18:19.180
is based on radical
innovation as opposed

01:18:19.180 --> 01:18:23.050
to incremental innovation,
which means that if you really

01:18:23.050 --> 01:18:26.410
want disruptive capitalism
and the potential gains

01:18:26.410 --> 01:18:28.600
of innovation that
can derive from it,

01:18:28.600 --> 01:18:31.120
you've got to think hard about
radical innovation, not just

01:18:31.120 --> 01:18:33.690
incremental advance.

01:18:33.690 --> 01:18:37.130
So in our system,
that means in turn,

01:18:37.130 --> 01:18:39.430
you gotta think about
that early stage R&D

01:18:39.430 --> 01:18:43.500
too, because that's the real
contributor to radical advance

01:18:43.500 --> 01:18:45.540
as opposed to industries
development, which

01:18:45.540 --> 01:18:47.316
is largely incremental.

01:18:47.316 --> 01:18:48.070
You with me?

01:18:51.280 --> 01:18:53.800
So Atkinson argues
that technology

01:18:53.800 --> 01:18:57.040
is the skeleton on which
an economy is formed,

01:18:57.040 --> 01:19:01.810
and every half century or
so, the skeleton changes

01:19:01.810 --> 01:19:04.600
as these waves come about.

01:19:04.600 --> 01:19:06.910
The changes are not steady.

01:19:06.910 --> 01:19:09.490
They can be very clustered.

01:19:09.490 --> 01:19:11.830
This is not a smooth wave.

01:19:11.830 --> 01:19:14.710
There should have been
lots of erratic lines

01:19:14.710 --> 01:19:16.720
in the wave theory
diagram I showed you.

01:19:19.380 --> 01:19:22.450
Now Carlotta Perez is a
great growth economist

01:19:22.450 --> 01:19:24.460
who taught at the
University of Sussex

01:19:24.460 --> 01:19:27.850
and worked with
Chris Freeman there,

01:19:27.850 --> 01:19:33.800
and she argues that it's
not just the economy

01:19:33.800 --> 01:19:36.650
changes, but the politics,
social relations, and the how

01:19:36.650 --> 01:19:38.930
and where we live that changes.

01:19:38.930 --> 01:19:42.440
And it's also how we organize
our education system,

01:19:42.440 --> 01:19:44.508
and how our culture
in turn, which

01:19:44.508 --> 01:19:46.800
is driven by some of these
factors, shapes our beliefs.

01:19:46.800 --> 01:19:50.780
So, quote, "the logic of
the techno-economic paradigm

01:19:50.780 --> 01:19:53.810
reaches well beyond the economic
sphere to become a general

01:19:53.810 --> 01:19:57.830
and shared organization
common sense of the period."

01:19:57.830 --> 01:19:59.620
So here's an idea here--

01:19:59.620 --> 01:20:01.100
a techno-economic paradigm.

01:20:04.090 --> 01:20:06.980
A paradigm that includes
technology, but therefore

01:20:06.980 --> 01:20:08.870
reaches deep into economics.

01:20:08.870 --> 01:20:12.830
So there's a driving
paradigm in a society

01:20:12.830 --> 01:20:14.610
that connects these two.

01:20:14.610 --> 01:20:17.270
I'll argue later in
class that the paradigm

01:20:17.270 --> 01:20:18.430
is even bigger than this.

01:20:21.230 --> 01:20:24.270
And that becomes, in a
way, the order of things.

01:20:24.270 --> 01:20:29.240
So I think we'll kind
of wrap it up here

01:20:29.240 --> 01:20:32.570
in terms of talking
about Atkinson because we

01:20:32.570 --> 01:20:34.010
need to move on.

01:20:34.010 --> 01:20:39.960
But Beth, you've got
Atkinson as well, right?

01:20:39.960 --> 01:20:41.450
And I think,
actually, if you speak

01:20:41.450 --> 01:20:43.250
into the mic in the center--

01:20:43.250 --> 01:20:47.660
and I'll move this
laptop slightly

01:20:47.660 --> 01:20:49.430
so you've got a
direct line there.

