01:21:14.890 --> 01:21:16.900
Is it something that's
unique to the US

01:21:16.900 --> 01:21:19.450
and to more developed
countries, or can we

01:21:19.450 --> 01:21:23.140
apply it anywhere in the world?

01:21:23.140 --> 01:21:24.850
Are there actions
that can be taken

01:21:24.850 --> 01:21:29.490
to minimize these troughs to
shorten how long depressions

01:21:29.490 --> 01:21:30.730
may be?

01:21:30.730 --> 01:21:33.190
And then a lot of
just about what

01:21:33.190 --> 01:21:35.110
is technology's
effect on society,

01:21:35.110 --> 01:21:36.430
and what it should we--

01:21:36.430 --> 01:21:38.440
should the government
be doing things

01:21:38.440 --> 01:21:42.910
to counteract technology's
effect on society

01:21:42.910 --> 01:21:48.164
or is it a good thing that
we're seeing these effects?

01:21:48.164 --> 01:21:50.950
So just a few points
before we go into that

01:21:50.950 --> 01:21:53.820
that I found interesting.

01:21:53.820 --> 01:21:56.220
So Atkinson writes
with the belief

01:21:56.220 --> 01:21:58.290
that this new
economy is something

01:21:58.290 --> 01:22:00.780
that is permanent--
it's not just a blip.

01:22:00.780 --> 01:22:02.280
And I think that's
something that we

01:22:02.280 --> 01:22:04.980
can kind of work with
as an assumption when

01:22:04.980 --> 01:22:06.660
we discuss this.

01:22:06.660 --> 01:22:09.020
But if you have specific
things that you can point out

01:22:09.020 --> 01:22:14.490
that it is just a blip, I'd be
interested to hear this too.

01:22:14.490 --> 01:22:16.380
And so the concept
of this new economy

01:22:16.380 --> 01:22:19.170
forms new businesses,
labor organizations,

01:22:19.170 --> 01:22:22.710
educational systems,
cultural beliefs

01:22:22.710 --> 01:22:24.720
I think is especially
relevant today

01:22:24.720 --> 01:22:28.650
as we're kind of seeing a lot
of interesting political things

01:22:28.650 --> 01:22:29.830
arise.

01:22:29.830 --> 01:22:33.480
And it says with
every disruption,

01:22:33.480 --> 01:22:36.200
entrenched interests will push
back and may resist the change,

01:22:36.200 --> 01:22:37.950
and so I think that's
something that would

01:22:37.950 --> 01:22:39.033
be interesting to discuss.

01:22:41.940 --> 01:22:44.107
So before we go into the
social aspects, I want to--

01:22:44.107 --> 01:22:45.732
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN:
I just want to say,

01:22:45.732 --> 01:22:47.600
Beth, I really like that--

01:22:47.600 --> 01:22:48.530
your last point here.

01:22:48.530 --> 01:22:50.810
In other words, we are
seeing very significant

01:22:50.810 --> 01:22:52.940
social disruption today.

01:22:52.940 --> 01:22:58.370
And we may be able to connect it
back to the IT innovation wave

01:22:58.370 --> 01:23:01.310
which, frankly, the
upper middle class has

01:23:01.310 --> 01:23:05.330
ridden to unparalleled success,
but left a lot of people

01:23:05.330 --> 01:23:06.500
behind--

01:23:06.500 --> 01:23:07.578
maybe.

01:23:07.578 --> 01:23:08.870
Is that what you're driving at?

01:23:08.870 --> 01:23:11.655
AUDIENCE: That's kind of what
I was going to talk about.

01:23:11.655 --> 01:23:14.450
So I guess you can jump
into that actually.

01:23:14.450 --> 01:23:17.510
So we talk about how
these long waves increase

01:23:17.510 --> 01:23:21.020
overall quality of life
perhaps at the national scale,

01:23:21.020 --> 01:23:24.080
but they do tend to be unequal.

01:23:24.080 --> 01:23:26.450
So should the government
have responsibility

01:23:26.450 --> 01:23:29.300
for correcting this
inequity, should it just

01:23:29.300 --> 01:23:33.070
be focusing on total efficiency
for the nation as a whole,

01:23:33.070 --> 01:23:37.730
and how can it balance the idea
that some parts of the country

01:23:37.730 --> 01:23:40.850
may be worse off while
others are better off?

01:23:40.850 --> 01:23:42.320
So it's very broad and open.

01:23:42.320 --> 01:23:44.570
AUDIENCE: Could you repeat
the question one more time?

01:23:44.570 --> 01:23:46.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:23:46.820 --> 01:23:49.730
So the paper claims
that these long waves

01:23:49.730 --> 01:23:53.000
increase the general quality
of life, maybe at, like,

01:23:53.000 --> 01:23:54.410
a national scale.

01:23:54.410 --> 01:23:59.670
But the benefits are likely
to be uneven based on maybe

01:23:59.670 --> 01:24:03.650
who's most prepared to take
on the technological changes.

01:24:03.650 --> 01:24:05.720
So should the government
have a responsibility

01:24:05.720 --> 01:24:08.480
to increase the equity?

01:24:08.480 --> 01:24:11.510
Should they be more focused
on just total efficiency?

01:24:11.510 --> 01:24:14.060
How do we handle this
and the societal changes

01:24:14.060 --> 01:24:15.300
that arise from it?

01:24:15.300 --> 01:24:18.380
I think there is some
talk that that's kind of--

01:24:18.380 --> 01:24:21.500
that wave of populism
has been very

01:24:21.500 --> 01:24:24.320
evident in recent elections,
so is that something

01:24:24.320 --> 01:24:26.495
that the government
should be intervening with

01:24:26.495 --> 01:24:28.120
or should it be up
to the free markets?

01:24:33.488 --> 01:24:35.440
AUDIENCE: I guess I'll jump in.

01:24:35.440 --> 01:24:37.790
I think the major implications
of innovation wave theory

01:24:37.790 --> 01:24:39.507
is just that we should
always be nervous

01:24:39.507 --> 01:24:41.090
because if we don't
get the next wave,

01:24:41.090 --> 01:24:42.632
then our economy is
kind of screwed--

01:24:42.632 --> 01:24:44.480
we won't be number one anymore.

01:24:44.480 --> 01:24:46.580
And so, like, some key
technologies-- or also

01:24:46.580 --> 01:24:48.890
some examples of what could
happen in the future is,

01:24:48.890 --> 01:24:52.230
like, there's certain
asteroid belts that are

01:24:52.230 --> 01:24:54.950
worth quintillion's of dollars.

01:24:54.950 --> 01:24:57.270
So if we happen to
say, oh, you know

01:24:57.270 --> 01:24:59.720
what, we're just going to
not really focus on having

01:24:59.720 --> 01:25:01.190
rapid innovation in Japan.

01:25:01.190 --> 01:25:03.380
Or China says, oh,
actually, we're not really

01:25:03.380 --> 01:25:05.930
focusing on this at all--

01:25:05.930 --> 01:25:09.050
let's do a Manhattan
Project for going into space

01:25:09.050 --> 01:25:10.328
and being able to mine.

01:25:10.328 --> 01:25:12.620
And they can go in and they
can get quintillion dollars

01:25:12.620 --> 01:25:17.210
into their economy, then their
GDP is looking pretty good.

01:25:17.210 --> 01:25:18.930
Other implications
are say somebody

01:25:18.930 --> 01:25:21.590
focuses a lot on biotech
to the point where

01:25:21.590 --> 01:25:25.700
they can engineer diseases
that only they can counter.

01:25:25.700 --> 01:25:28.460
And then they start doing
biological warfare because they

01:25:28.460 --> 01:25:30.650
know the US has nuclear arms.

01:25:30.650 --> 01:25:33.496
So that's a different
way they can branch out.

01:25:33.496 --> 01:25:37.518
So I guess it's kind
of this idea of we're

01:25:37.518 --> 01:25:39.310
never really on top,
or when you're on top,

01:25:39.310 --> 01:25:41.150
everyone is shooting
for you, I guess.

01:25:41.150 --> 01:25:43.700
Where we could say, yeah,
we're number one, but also

01:25:43.700 --> 01:25:47.450
say we really need to
keep innovating and think

01:25:47.450 --> 01:25:49.160
about how we're structuring it.

01:25:49.160 --> 01:25:51.290
Because the future is
always going to be-- well,

01:25:51.290 --> 01:25:54.150
time is pretty much just
indicating that change

01:25:54.150 --> 01:25:55.670
is happening all the time.

01:25:55.670 --> 01:25:59.170
So we probably won't be where
we're at, and we probably--

01:25:59.170 --> 01:26:01.320
I'm thinking we don't
want to go down,

01:26:01.320 --> 01:26:04.730
but that's really up to
the US and its citizens

01:26:04.730 --> 01:26:07.850
to decide every
single generation.

01:26:07.850 --> 01:26:10.153
AUDIENCE: I might come
at it from a little bit

01:26:10.153 --> 01:26:10.820
different angle.

01:26:10.820 --> 01:26:14.480
I think we've been talking a lot
about sort of a capital based

01:26:14.480 --> 01:26:16.700
innovation and how that might--

01:26:16.700 --> 01:26:19.790
the IT boom and how things
might be a little different

01:26:19.790 --> 01:26:22.610
structured on, like,
a capital side.

01:26:22.610 --> 01:26:25.362
We might have--
just kind of look

01:26:25.362 --> 01:26:27.445
at the effect of human
capital and in the universe

01:26:27.445 --> 01:26:28.410
of innovation.

01:26:28.410 --> 01:26:31.460
But I think there's an
important piece here

01:26:31.460 --> 01:26:34.730
where we see a lot of growth
in the upper middle class

01:26:34.730 --> 01:26:38.330
because they're prepared
to handle [INAUDIBLE]

01:26:38.330 --> 01:26:42.480
a lot of the sort of more human
aspects of where we're going.

01:26:42.480 --> 01:26:45.350
But you see sort
of this transition

01:26:45.350 --> 01:26:48.782
as we look forward into
sort of management styles

01:26:48.782 --> 01:26:50.990
and kind of structuring
things, which is a little bit

01:26:50.990 --> 01:26:52.698
more high level, which
again lends itself

01:26:52.698 --> 01:26:53.790
to the middle class.

01:26:53.790 --> 01:26:55.880
Which I think if
we were looking to,

01:26:55.880 --> 01:26:59.570
as a corrective
measure for government

01:26:59.570 --> 01:27:01.610
widespread involvement,
there is this sort

01:27:01.610 --> 01:27:04.160
of public need for the
smoothing and transition.

01:27:04.160 --> 01:27:07.410
So that, like, you see the
highs for those that are high,

01:27:07.410 --> 01:27:08.980
but you don't see
the aggressive lows

01:27:08.980 --> 01:27:11.870
for those that are low sort
of passed over and made

01:27:11.870 --> 01:27:14.170
obsolete structurally
by this innovation.

01:27:14.170 --> 01:27:17.360
And I think there's
a greater need

01:27:17.360 --> 01:27:22.640
for kind of renewed investment
in sort of this human capital.

01:27:22.640 --> 01:27:24.710
I guess at the end
of the '60s, you

01:27:24.710 --> 01:27:28.360
had the GI Bill which helped
kind of a lot of folks

01:27:28.360 --> 01:27:32.750
get reintegrated in
sort of public education

01:27:32.750 --> 01:27:35.330
and greater institutional
or secondary education

01:27:35.330 --> 01:27:38.267
at postgraduate increased
sort of en masse.

01:27:38.267 --> 01:27:40.100
For a lot of different
reasons, that sort of

01:27:40.100 --> 01:27:43.270
helped ride the wave into
the 1990s because of that.

01:27:43.270 --> 01:27:48.575
But these sort of things
now, it's [INAUDIBLE]..

01:27:53.313 --> 01:27:54.730
There's a lot of
different changes

01:27:54.730 --> 01:27:56.600
that may happen a lot of more
frequently now and a lot more

01:27:56.600 --> 01:27:57.100
connected.

01:27:57.100 --> 01:28:00.550
So there's less room for
error because we can't really

01:28:00.550 --> 01:28:05.520
isolate ourselves in sort
of this US national system.

01:28:05.520 --> 01:28:07.310
But as a general
[INAUDIBLE] summary,

01:28:07.310 --> 01:28:10.310
I think you get a lot of these
interesting events happening

01:28:10.310 --> 01:28:14.200
a lot more quickly, so the highs
can get higher a lot faster

01:28:14.200 --> 01:28:16.003
and the lows can get
lower a lot faster.

01:28:16.003 --> 01:28:18.420
And so if we were sort of to
look for a governmental role,

01:28:18.420 --> 01:28:20.840
it'd be sort of probably
smoothing out these lows

01:28:20.840 --> 01:28:22.340
rather than focusing--

01:28:22.340 --> 01:28:23.590
AUDIENCE: Or insurance.

01:28:23.590 --> 01:28:25.250
AUDIENCE: Insurance-- yeah.

01:28:25.250 --> 01:28:28.910
Investment backing and
equity capital so you have--

01:28:28.910 --> 01:28:30.893
you're more able to kind
of take these shots.

01:28:30.893 --> 01:28:33.310
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: So Rasheed,
that's really interesting,

01:28:33.310 --> 01:28:35.420
and you're driving
us to a perspective

01:28:35.420 --> 01:28:38.550
here that innovation
waves may be

01:28:38.550 --> 01:28:42.050
a way, at least in the shorter
term, for the rich to get

01:28:42.050 --> 01:28:47.630
richer and to create a
larger underclass, right?

01:28:47.630 --> 01:28:51.360
If we look at the Industrial
Revolution, the workout

01:28:51.360 --> 01:28:54.075
period of doing the
adjustments for the workforce--

01:28:54.075 --> 01:28:55.700
I mean, that's a 100
year long project.

01:28:59.150 --> 01:29:01.250
I think that recent
election results may tell us

01:29:01.250 --> 01:29:04.790
that we don't have the kind
time to play with as we work out

01:29:04.790 --> 01:29:07.220
the latest innovation waves.

01:29:07.220 --> 01:29:10.940
Now is an alternative to
bring on another wave?

01:29:13.580 --> 01:29:15.980
And then maybe all
waves are not the same

01:29:15.980 --> 01:29:18.020
in terms of their class,
and structural effects,

01:29:18.020 --> 01:29:20.240
and deterministic effects.

01:29:20.240 --> 01:29:23.900
So if Martha's innovation wave
around new energy technology

01:29:23.900 --> 01:29:27.560
that she spends her
life on comes about,

01:29:27.560 --> 01:29:30.590
that may be a big net
generator of employment

01:29:30.590 --> 01:29:34.410
overall as opposed to an
IT software wave which

01:29:34.410 --> 01:29:36.410
appears to be less so.

01:29:36.410 --> 01:29:38.480
So different waves may
have different kind

01:29:38.480 --> 01:29:41.900
of underlying structural
features for the society.

01:29:41.900 --> 01:29:44.741
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:29:44.741 --> 01:29:48.460
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: [LAUGHS]
Right, unless we get on it.

01:29:48.460 --> 01:29:49.940
Martha, you better hurry up.

01:29:49.940 --> 01:29:50.900
That's all I can say.

01:29:50.900 --> 01:29:52.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:29:52.900 --> 01:29:55.192
WILLIAM BONVILLIAN: What are
you saying this class was?

01:29:55.192 --> 01:29:57.466
AUDIENCE: I wanted to
come back to a point

01:29:57.466 --> 01:29:59.247
that Beth made right
at the beginning

01:29:59.247 --> 01:30:01.580
when she said that we're going
to work on the assumption

01:30:01.580 --> 01:30:06.045
that our economy is an
innovation driven economy.

01:30:06.045 --> 01:30:07.670
And I think that all
of us in this room

01:30:07.670 --> 01:30:09.620
are probably on board with that.

01:30:09.620 --> 01:30:12.630
A lot of economists
are on board with that,

01:30:12.630 --> 01:30:15.890
but then Bill made the point
that our two-party system

01:30:15.890 --> 01:30:21.200
is arranged mostly around
these older views of economics.

01:30:21.200 --> 01:30:25.930
So why haven't one or
